This course was for students who had never studied French or who had had very little exposure to the language. Most students with previous French should have enrolled in French 121 (elementary French for "false beginners"). All students who had already studied French elsewhere are required to take the placement test. Class work emphasized the development of speaking and listening comprehension, reinforced by work in reading and writing. The course included an introduction to French and Francophone culture. Out-of-class homework required work with the Internet, audio and video materials. &#8232;

Students enjoyed the class and seemed excited about pursuing their French studies in the next level. Students wrote that due to the course, they were interested in pursuing French studies “more seriously” and were committed “to excelling.” From this class, students became interested in “learning about French and French culture.”&#8232;&#8232;

The students enjoyed Professor Edelstein’s teaching, praising her ability “to make complex concepts easy to understand” and her “insights…above and beyond the basic textbook material.” Other students described her as “fantastic” and “patient.”&#8232;

Students were also happy with the pace of the class, especially at the beginner level. The class “moved at the perfect speed, enough to be challenging but not too fast as to be unmanageable.” The students did not feel lost or confused, and they also enjoyed the grammatical exercises, finding them helpful to their French education.

